{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[2]", "headings": "['Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample']"}, "page_content": "Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample\nFrequently, these microsamples exhibit incomplete data on one or more attributes due to errors in data collection, or the respondents intentionally withholding information or not collecting it to ensure privacy. Additionally, to improve the attribute richness of the microsample, it can be combined with supplemental data from other sources. For example, a travel survey in a certain region from multiple distinct organizations can be combined to add more data and attributes to the microsample. However, there may be situations where one or more attributes are absent from either of the surveys. Hence, there is a need for an imputation algorithm that can be used to estimate missing values based on data that was observed or measured in a microsample. This will ensure that the synthetic population that population synthesis models generate is complete.", "type": "Document"}}